                     <p style="float:left; width:450px; height:auto;">{exp:snippet total="140" word="" ellipsis="..."}<p>
	<big>If you&rsquo;ve ever taken part in online <strong>discussion forums</strong>,&nbsp; you&rsquo;ll know that they can be frustrating. It&rsquo;s quite common for participation to be low, or for a discussion to be dominated by one or two participants, with nobody else contributing very much.</big></p>
<p>
	<big>Of course, you can never guarantee that all students on a module will contribute fully and meaningfully&nbsp; to a discussion forum, but there are certain steps you can take which make it more likely that the discussions generated will be worthwhile.<br />
	<br />
	To start with, take a look at the short video from the University of New South Wales which gives an overview of <strong>moderating discussions</strong>. They have also created a useful PDF guide which you can download from the link below.<br />
	<br />
	Finally, take a look at some of the <strong>practical suggestions</strong> in the panel below the video.</big></p> 
                     {/exp:snippet}
                     <a href="http://www.celtelearning.org/weblearn/detail/moderating-online-discussions"><b><i>read more >></i></b></a> <br /><br /> <a href="{path=weblearn}">This entry is from the <b>Weblearn</b> channel</a>
                     </p>
            <a href="http://www.celtelearning.org/weblearn/detail/moderating-online-discussions">  <h3>Moderating Online Discussions </h3></a>
            {/if}
