                     <p style="float:left; width:450px; height:auto;">{exp:snippet total="140" word="" ellipsis="..."}<p>
	<br />
	It&rsquo;s easy to think that by uploading a lot of content to Weblearn, students will automatically be able to find that content and know what to do with it. Although certain content may not require much explanation or interaction, it&rsquo;s usually a good idea to provide a context for any learning content you upload or create, so that students know exactly where to find it, what to do with it and what is expected of them &ndash; this can help to create a more effective and positive learning environment.&nbsp;<br />
	<br />
	There&#39;s a good introduction to the concept of scaffolding learning content from Faculty Focus which you can read on the link below:<br />
	<br />
	<a href="http://www.facultyfocus.com/articles/instructional-design/scaffolding-student-learning-tips-for-getting-started/">http://www.facultyfocus.com/articles/instructional-design/scaffolding-student-learning-tips-for-getting-started/</a><br />
	<br />
	For practical advice and suggestions, have a look at the tabbed content below.</p> 
                     {/exp:snippet}
