                     <p style="float:left; width:450px; height:auto;">{exp:snippet total="140" word="" ellipsis="..."}<p>
	<br />
	The latest version of Blackboard has some improved communication tools which allow you and your students to create and sustain <em>dialogue</em>. However, it can be difficult to know which of these tools (if any) is suitable for your purpose, as certain tools probably lend themselves better to certain types of task.<br />
	<br />
	For example, if you&rsquo;re looking for an online space where a student can reflect on their learning and share their thoughts, and prefer to keep this inside Weblearn, an online J<strong>ournal </strong>is probably the best option. On the other hand, if you want students to communicate and, for example, comment on each others&rsquo; ideas, then a <strong>Discussion Forum </strong>or <strong>Group Blog</strong> might be a better choice.<br />
	<br />
	This learning resource will give an overview of these tools and help you decide which is the one you need.&nbsp;<br />
	<br />
	For a quick overview of these communication tools, have a look at the attached guide <strong>&#39;Getting Started with Interactive Tools</strong>&#39; from Blackboard.</p> 
                     {/exp:snippet}
                     <a href="http://www.celtelearning.org/weblearn/detail/blogs-journals-discussions-which-to-choose"><b><i>read more >></i></b></a> <br /><br /> <a href="{path=weblearn}">This entry is from the <b>Weblearn</b> channel</a>
                     </p>
            <a href="http://www.celtelearning.org/weblearn/detail/blogs-journals-discussions-which-to-choose">  <h3>Blogs, Journals &amp; Discussions – which to choose? </h3></a>
            {/if}
