                     <p style="float:left; width:450px; height:auto;">{exp:snippet total="140" word="" ellipsis="..."}<p>
	<b>Google Drive</b> is an increibly versatile addition to any teaching situation, whether it&#39;s primary school age, or higher education. Teachers benefit because they can share teaching materials, they are easily commented on or otherwsie notated. They also have <em>&#39;versioning</em>&#39; (more on that article #2), they can be updated without having to reshare, and more. Students can also benefit hugely, not only becaise of all of the above, but also they can work with each other - in group work - using Google Docs Drive for document creating, sharing, or other file sharing.</p>
<p>
	<strong><em>Google Drive</em></strong> gives you</p>
<ul>
	<li>
		5gb of space online</li>
	<li>
		You can store anything, but only some file types can be edited online</li>
	<li>
		Whoever you share anything with needs to have their own Google account</li>
	<li>
		Google Drive lets you have multiple isntances of your files, on multiple devices. As long as they are connected to the internet, they will synch automatically</li>
</ul>
<p>
	&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	This article focuses primarily on the basics of Google Docs and Google Presentations.</p> 
                     {/exp:snippet}
                     <a href="http://www.celtelearning.org/tutorials/detail/google-docs-and-presentations"><b><i>read more >></i></b></a> <br /><br /> <a href="{path=tutorials}">This entry is from the <b>Tutorials</b> channel</a>
                     </p>
            <a href="http://www.celtelearning.org/tutorials/detail/google-docs-and-presentations">  <h3>Google Docs &amp; Presentations </h3></a>
            {/if}
